{"type":"assistant","message":{"id":"067a99587af17f4e1a8ad9dac06ea435","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `ODUS_IFA` is more populated than the `odus-constants.ts` ODUS — it has all 16 entries with `significado` (longer), `quizilas` (currently mostly empty arrays in this view), `preceitos` (1-2 each), `orixaRegente`, `elementos`.\n\nThe two files have slightly different naming conventions:\n- `odus-constants.ts` ODUS: 1-16, \"Ogbe\", \"Ejiokô\", \"Etogundá\", \"Irosun\", \"Oxê\", \"Obará\", \"Odi\", \"Ejionile\", \"Ossá\", \"Ofun\", \"Owarin\", \"Ejilaxebô\", \"Oturupon\", \"Oturá\", \"Iká\", \"Ofurufu\"\n- `odus-ifa-data.ts` ODUS_IFA: 1-16, \"Ogbe (Oxé)\", \"Ejiokô\", \"Etogundá\", \"Irosun\", \"Oxê (Ogunda)\", \"Obará\", \"Odi\", ...\n\nBoth are derived from IDEIA.md §5 (canonical). The D-044 lesson confirmed that Pilar 4 has 15 names with Eji instead of Ogbe by design, but the canonical lists have 16 names.\n\nFor F-219, the simplest, most surgical approach: enhance `glossary.ts` to look up real Odu data from the available canonical source. Let me see what's currently exported and how to use it.\n\nApproach 1: import `ODUS_IFA` and `getOduPorNumero` from `@akasha/core-odus`\nApproach 2: add `glossary` to `@akasha/core-odus` (proper place but bigger refactor)\nApproach 3: add inline Odu data map to glossary.ts (locally)\n\nThe \"use canonical source\" rule says Approach 1 is correct. The Pilar 4 ethics invariant is satisfied because we derive from `ODUS_IFA` which is itself derived from `IDEIA.md §5` (canonical).\n\nBut the function signature in glossary.ts is:\n```typescript\nbuildOduGlossary(odues: unknown): OduGlossarySection | null\n```\n\nThe input `odues` is the Odu object from a chart, not a number. The Odu has `oduName` and probably a number. Let me check what the chart Odu looks like.\n\nActually, looking more carefully, this is a F-219 surgical fix:\n- The function takes an Odu name (string) or array of strings\n- Returns glossary section\n- Currently returns placeholders\n\nThe simplest fix: when the input is a string Odu name, look up the real data from `ODUS_IFA` by name match and return real data. If not found, fall back to current placeholder behavior.\n\nLet me look at what Odu names come in. The input could be:\n- Array of strings: `['Ogbe', 'Oyeku']` \n- Object: `{ oduName: 'Ogbe' }`\n\nThe canonical ODUS_IFA names are: 'Ogbe (Oxé)', 'Ejiokô', 'Etogundá', 'Irosun', 'Oxê (Ogunda)', 'Obará', 'Odi', ...\n\nI need to handle the name normalization. The stub uses `name` as-is. The canonical source uses `Ogbe (Oxé)`. I need a name matcher.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The cleanest implementation:\n1. Take the Odu name as input\n2. Try to find a matching Odu in ODUS_IFA (normalize: strip parentheticals, lowercase comparison)\n3. If found, return real data (`significado` → `essencia`, `quizilas[0] || placeholder` → `quizila`, `preceitos.join(', ')` → `conselho`)\n4. If not found, fall back to current placeholder\n\nLet me check if `@akasha/core-odus` is a workspace dep of `apps/akasha-portal`:","signature":"a4adc994246b7dbf6a488f43d0b994b3766f3ee34d874d27927be63051596168"}],"model":"MiniMax-M3","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":0,"service_tier":"standard"},"service_tier":"standard","context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"efa9633d-4bd4-4eaf-8cc7-696bf2eda76b","uuid":"1483bec1-5c9b-403e-bfd7-15d05709856e"}
